<a href="http://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=/8900/24.com/Web/DailySun/News/National_Article&sz=300x250&c=828077816&t=artid%3dc32878f2-c1f5-4a3e-b5ee-1f92da896568%26accreditation%3ddaily+sun%26posno%3d2" target="_blank"><img src="http://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=/8900/24.com/Web/DailySun/News/National_Article&sz=300x250&c=828077816&t=artid%3dc32878f2-c1f5-4a3e-b5ee-1f92da896568%26accreditation%3ddaily+sun%26posno%3d2" border="0" alt=""></a>During these past two weeks alone, Sedibeng cluster police, together with the initiation traditional surgeons committee and others, rescued 170 boys from initiation camps in the Vaal area.Two weeks ago, the commision ordered the suspension of all initiation camps and activities in Gauteng until next year, meaning there should have been no summer intake of initiates.But that didn’t stop fake initiation chiefs in the Vaal from building camps.Two weeks ago, 90 initiates were found between the Vaal and Sasolburg and last week, another 80 were rescued and camps between Orange Farm and Poortjie were demolished.Initiation chief and chairman of the Sedibeng surgeons committee, ntate Sipinare Mofokeng, said those who continue the camps are disrespecting the law.“They are taking the law for granted and are undermining our age old culture with their fake camps.“This shows how much they disrespect the commission as well,” he said.Mofokeng said the best way to deal with illegal chiefs was to lock them up.“If they are locked up, then they will realise how serious the matter is.” Mofokeng said they would continue the raids and rescue kidnapped youngsters until the last day of intake, whic is normally around 16 December.Commission spokesman Mpiyakhe Mkholo told Daily Sun even though they had made the announcement about initiations being suspended, local municipalities had to carry out the ban. 
